<h1 class="sectionedit1" id="bash_tipscolors_and_formatting_ansivt100_control_sequences">Bash tips: Colors and formatting (ANSI/VT100 Control sequences)</h1>
<div class="level1">

<p>
The <strong>ANSI/VT100</strong> terminals and terminal emulators are not just able to display black and white text ;
they can display <strong>colors</strong> and formatted texts thanks to <strong>escape sequences</strong>. Those sequences are composed of
the <strong>Escape character</strong> (often represented by “<code>^[</code>” or “<code>&lt;Esc&gt;</code>”) followed by some other characters:
“<code>&lt;Esc&gt;[</code><span style="color: red"><em>FormatCode</em></span><code>m</code>”.
</p>

<p>
In Bash, the <code>&lt;Esc&gt;</code> character can be obtained with the following syntaxes:
</p>
<ul>
<li class="level1"><div class="li"> <code>\e</code></div>
</li>
<li class="level1"><div class="li"> <code>\033</code></div>
</li>
<li class="level1"><div class="li"> <code>\x1B</code></div>
</li>
</ul>

<p>
<em class="u">Examples:</em>
</p>
