<h2 class="sectionedit13" id="colors1">88/256 Colors</h2>
<div class="level2">

<p>
Some terminals (<span class="curid"><a href="https://misc.flogisoft.com/bash/tip_colors_and_formatting#terminals_compatibility" class="wikilink1" title="bash:tip_colors_and_formatting">see the compatibility list</a></span>) can support 88 or 256 colors. Here are the control sequences that permit you to use them.
</p>

<p>
<em class="u">NOTE¹</em>: The colors number <code>256</code> is only supported by <strong>vte</strong> (GNOME Terminal, XFCE4 Terminal, Nautilus Terminal, Terminator,…).
</p>

<p>
<em class="u">NOTE²</em>: The 88-colors terminals (like <strong>rxvt</strong>) does not have the same color map that the 256-colors terminals.
For showing the 88-colors terminals color map, run the “<span class="curid"><a href="https://misc.flogisoft.com/bash/tip_colors_and_formatting#colors2" class="wikilink1" title="bash:tip_colors_and_formatting">256-colors.sh</a></span>” script in a 88-colors terminal.
</p>

</div>

<h3 class="sectionedit14" id="foreground_text1">Foreground (text)</h3>
<div class="level3">

<p>
For using one of the 256 colors on the foreground (text color), the control sequence is
“<code>&lt;Esc&gt;[38;5;</code><span style="color: red;"><em>ColorNumber</em></span><code>m</code>” where <code>ColorNumber</code> is one of the following colors:
</p>

<p>
